passages.text: The investment case for Thai banks continues to be driven by capital management. A faster pace and transmission of rate cuts does dent the thesis, but not derail it. KBank is in the midst of a rare increase in shareholding from an unrelated party, which appears unsolicited. These factors, among others, have aligned management's incentives to increase payouts more aggressively and evaluate buybacks. We forecast \(\sim 70\%\) average cash payout (including special) in 2025- 27, with an additional \(\sim 15\%\) of 2026- 27 profits being used for buybacks. This adds up to \(8 - 12\%\) total yield on the stock in 2025- 27, with a high degree of visibility. KTB should get a boost of \(\sim 19\%\) of profits this year (most likely) from Thai Air listing, part of which should be paid out this or next year. We forecast \(6 - 8\%\) cash yield and \(2\%\) buyback yield at the bank, leading to \(8 - 10\%\) total yield in 2026/27. TTB's buyback phase has ended, and current rules suggest a resumption in Feb- 26. Hence, we expect a degree of consolidation in the stock price and downgrade to Neutral. A phase of time correction and possibly price correction can allow opportunities to scale up positions. BBL and SCB stay N, as it is tough to anticipate a payout increase in both these stocks; with SCB already at \(80\%\) payout and \(\sim 8\%\) 2025/26 DY. Tisco stays UW, as the exceptional payout over the last decade is being replicated elsewhere. Hence, premium valuations should come off.

Policy transmission: We are reducing our forecasts by \(2 - 6\%\) for the big four banks for 2025- 27E, as transmission has been earlier and faster. This is net negative for NIM (34/15bps y/y decline in \(25 / 26\) at the Big 4), as we factor in 2 more rate cuts by the end of the year (link). Loan yield reduction is a net positive for asset quality, with the effects of easing monetary policy percolating to the broader economy. Hence, despite lower earnings, banks are comfortable increasing capital returns, in the form of dividends as well as buybacks.

Capital management: DPS and buybacks are incremental drivers of stock prices, hence the sector has done well YTD despite negative revisions; we believe it will continue to do so. KBank is our top pick, as cash DPS yield is highest for the stock for 2025- 26. Interim DPS of Bt2 was in- line with our forecasts and a positive surprise for the Street. KTB is a close second. As soon as BoT/SEC revise the buyback regulations, the bank should start the process. This should be a meaningful catalyst for the stock. BBL offers deep value, with a possibility of capital management, but probability of such an action remains low. SCB has already optimized payout at \(80\%\) . Almost similar for Tisco.

TTB: The bank has bought back Bt5.1bn of stocks YTD vs a budget of Bt7bn. A significant cooling off period is now in place, which means buybacks can fully start in Feb- 26. We believe TTB did not conduct enough buybacks earlier. In the year, which led to the bank missing the budget. To be fair, there are quite a few clauses regarding buybacks, spread across various regulations. This limits nimbleness in execution. Our analysis (Fig. 13) shows that the bank was able to figure the limitations in course of the year, and increased buybacks to a pace of \(21\%\) of daily volumes since May- 25 (vs \(7.5\%\) in Feb- Apr). We expect Bt8/6.3bn in buybacks in 2026/27. Yet, the pause for next 6M, and eventual end of tax- related benefits by FY27 limits RoE/DPS visibility beyond a point.

The investment case for Thai banks continues to be driven by capital management. A faster pace and transmission of rate cuts does dent the thesis, but does not derail it.

KBank is in the midst of a rare increase in shareholding from an unrelated party, which appears unsolicited. These factors, among others, have aligned management's incentives to increase payouts more aggressively and evaluate buybacks. We forecast a \(\sim 70\%\) average cash payout (regular and special) in 2025- 27, with an additional \(\sim 15\%\) of 2026- 27 profits being used for buybacks. This adds up to \(8 - 12\%\) total yield on the stock in 2025- 27, with a high degree of visibility.

KTB should get a boost of \(\sim 19\%\) of profits this year (most likely) from the Thai Air listing. A part of these profits should be paid out this or next year. We forecast a \(\sim 7 - 8\%\) cash yield and \(\sim 2\%\) buyback yield at the bank, leading to a \(6 - 10\%\) total yield in 2025- 27. TTB's buyback phase has ended, and current rules suggest resumption in Feb- 26, hence we expect a degree of consolidation in the stock price. Accordingly, we downgrade the shares to Neutral. A phase of time correction and possibly price correction can allow opportunities to scale up positions. BBL and SCB stay Neutral, as it is tough to anticipate a payout increase in both these stocks; with SCB already at \(80\%\) payout and \(8.3\% /8.4\%\) 2025/26 DY. Tisco stays UW, as the exceptional payout over the last decade is being replicated elsewhere. Hence, the premium valuations for the stock should come off.

In the current cycle, there have been four rate cuts. During the first three cuts, which cumulatively amounted to 75bps, the average transmission to lending rates was at \(\sim 50\%\) . However, following the rate cut on August \(13^{\text{th}}\) 2025, which achieved a full \(100\%\) transmission, the overall pass- through on loans has increased to \(\sim 65\%\) . In contrast, during the rate hike cycle from August 2022 to October 2023, the average transmission rate was significantly higher, at \(\sim 80\%\) .

On the other hand, the transmission to deposit rates has decelerated following the latest rate cut. Initially, after the first three cuts, there was a \(70\%\) transmission in time deposits and around \(\sim 6\%\) for savings accounts. This transmission rate has now slowed down.

The bank took a lead on buybacks, with Bt5.1bn of buybacks conducted YTD vs budget of Bt7bn. A six- month cooling off period is now in place, which means the buyback can only start in Feb- 26. We believe TTB did not conduct enough buybacks earlier in the year, which led to the bank missing the budget. To be fair, the rules and regulations regarding buybacks have quite a few clauses, which limits nimbleness on execution. Our analysis (Figure 13) shows that the bank was able to figure the limitations in the course of the year, and increased buybacks to a pace of \(21\%\) of daily volumes since May- 25, but that pace was not enough to use up the quota. We expect Bt8/6.3bn in buybacks in 2026/27. Yet, the pause for the next 6M, and eventual end of tax- related benefits by FY27 limits visibility on RoE/DPS. At \(0.743 \cdot 25\) PB for \(6.3\%\) core RoE (8.3% headline RoE), we see the stock as fully valued. Hence, we downgrade to Neutral.

- Poor visibility on capital return (the stock offers the lowest dividend yield within our coverage), despite 18.2/16.7% bank/group CET1, low RWA growth and \(\sim 1\%\) EPS CAGR (2024-27E), limits our ability to take a positive view on the stock. At current levels, this equals 5.8-6.4% dividend yields, which are the lowest within our Thai bank coverage. Any possibility of capital management should lead to a sharp re-rating.- The bank has one of the largest LLR buffers in the region ( \(\sim 10\%\) LLR/Loans). Our calculations suggest that excess LLR should add c.30% to BVPS, after adjusting for potential delinquencies. This, along with a low retail portfolio (10-12% of mix), offers comfort on the bank's asset quality.- Permata should contribute \(\sim 16 - 17\%\) to group profits over 2025-27E, with a 12-14% contribution to group assets. This growth premium should lead to a narrowing of the valuation discount for the stock which showed up post the Permata transaction in 2019.- We think BBL's high capital buffers will allow the bank enough leeway to grow as credit demand picks up. Further, the bank should be the biggest beneficiary of a pick-up in Thailand's investment cycle.

- Management's RoE guidance in double digits appears credible; yet the path to \(10\%\) RoE through RoA improvement in a rate-cut environment appears rather difficult. Hence, we expect the bank to use capital management as a tool. Accordingly, we forecast dividends (regular and special) to move up, driving stock upside. We expect a higher total dividend payout ratio (including special) of \(67 - 75\%\) , with total DPS of Bt13.5/15.5/16.5 over 2025-27, respectively.- It does not appear that a share buyback is being actively considered at this time, though that remains a possibility, in our view. RWA growth at the bank is limited, which would lead to consistent capital accumulation. At the current juncture, with nominal GDP growth for the country running at \(-3\%\) and growth guidance at \(3 - 5\%\) , it is quite difficult to build a scenario where the retained capital can be used to deliver significant balance sheet growth, that too in a commercial manner.- The recently announced restructuring scheme offers visibility on asset quality holding up for 12-24 months. We forecast credit costs of 165/140bps in 2025/26, vs 190bps in 2024. This is a touch above mgm guidance of normalised provisions of 140-160bps.- SME loans comprise \(15\%\) of assets now, down from \(30\%\) 15 years ago. Further, the bank has unwound low RoRWA businesses in the past two years (high-yield consumer finance), which lends credence to the outlook for improving asset quality.- The CASA franchise for KBank \((80\%)\) is due to its strong branch network and best-in-class mobile application (KPLUS). However, the inability to lower CASA rates further poses NIM risks in an interest rate cut environment.- KBank's measured approach to digital changes gives us confidence in its ability to execute the digital strategy. The bank is well positioned in terms of its tech stack, product offerings, as well as building investments in the Web 3.0 space. However, these shifts will take time to show up in the bottom line.

Our Dec- 26 price target of Bt190 is based on a two- stage DDM valuation with a risk- free rate of \(3.5\%\) , cost of capital of \(11.9\%\) , and terminal growth rate of \(3.5\%\) . We use a fair P/BV multiple of \(0.71x\) with a normalized ROE of \(9.5\%\) .
